@node intro "Introduction"
Introduction :
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
My exams were approaching, and I discovered I had more than 50 vocabulary
lists I still had to learn by hard. Last year I'd made lists containing
these words, but now I thought to myself: why shouldn't I write a quick
and simple C-program to interrogate my vocabulary-knowledge ? 

I started coding, and after some hassles TTest was born. It's still a
very simple program, but if interest is shown I'd be willing to improve
this program and add some extra features.

As for now, I decided to release the program as-is, and offer other 
students worldwide a possible aid for their exams ...

I use it for vocabulary interrogation, but you can also use it for Maths 
and any other major you want to use it in. 

@endnode

@node execution "Execution"
Execution :
~~~~~~~~~~~
As I already said, TTest is still very simple, and therefor it's CLI
only. Perhaps it will run from WorkBench as well, but I doubt it. It
isn't meant to work from anything else than a standard Shell or CLI
window.

Running the program is very easy. You just enter 'TTest' followed by
the inputfile, and off you go.

Example:

 TTest input.dat

The Inputfile :
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The inputfile needs to have the following format:

 Question1
 Answer1
 Question2
 Answer2
 ...
 
The number of questions/answers is virtually unlimited, and thus the
program is suitable for many questions. I should add though, that the
number of characters for each question and/or answer is limited to
256. Anything longer will have TTest quit. But then again 256 characters
is more than enough for a question and/or an answer. If you want this
number to be increased, let @{" me " link author} know.

WARNING: The error-checking for longer inputs is still buggy, so using
         longer input-lines could cause a GURU !!!

@endnode

@node install "Installation"
Installation :
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This is the easy part ...
Installing TTest isn't very tough ; you just need to copy it somewhere
in your path, and that's all there is to be done. Simple, eh ?

e.g.

 copy TTest C:

Will copy the TTest program to your C: assign, which is always in the
path, and will always give you access to the TTest command.

@endnode

